data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. There are no calls to `Thread.Abort`, `Thread.Interrupt`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, and no `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks.

This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort migration):

You could simplify this with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`, which gives you cleaner concurrency and built-in `CancellationToken` support for free:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items,
                         CancellationToken token = default)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, new ParallelOptions
        {
            CancellationToken = token
        },
        item => Process(item, token));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken token)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Thread.Sleep(100); // or token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(100)
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is **purely optional** — your existing code is already .NET 8 compatible.
